{
  "answer": "**The work is *Andreas* by Cynewulf, Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis Old English poem narrates the apostle Andreas (Andrew) arriving at the cannibal city of Mermedonia, where the inhabitants devour strangers. He approaches the prison, where **\"before the barred doors guards were standing, seven together. Sudden death took them all, they fell, fame-less.\"** He enters, finds and embraces his fellow apostle Matthew, and leads out the captives: **\"one hundred and two, counted in number, and also forty, saved from the strife— he left not one of them under the city-lock fastened in fetters—and of women there yet, in addition to the host, one less than fifty he freed.\"**[^1]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-74e29a).",
